That was those kids messing
with the water main.

50
00:05:01,047 --> 00:05:04,323
- You should really quit those things.
- What for?

51
00:05:34,687 --> 00:05:37,520
Christmas comes a little early this year.

52
00:05:43,727 --> 00:05:46,719
There's our boy.
So, what do you say?

53
00:05:46,887 --> 00:05:51,403
- Does he stop in for coffee and a cruller?
- Let's give him a cruller.

54
00:05:51,567 --> 00:05:56,038
- Bingo! We have a winner.
- I can smell the fried dough over here.

55
00:05:56,207 --> 00:05:58,198
And there he is.

56
00:05:59,447 --> 00:06:01,802
Breakfast of champions, right there.

57
00:06:07,287 --> 00:06:09,562
We're losing him. I'll take
just a couple more.

58
00:06:09,727 --> 00:06:12,924
Say goodbye to Mr. Nicholas Easter.

59
00:06:13,487 --> 00:06:15,125
Who's next on the hit parade?

60
00:06:25,567 --> 00:06:26,886
Hi.

61
00:06:29,247 --> 00:06:31,203
Can I look at that candle?

62
00:06:32,607 --> 00:06:34,438
No, I'm sorry, the red one.

63
00:06:34,607 --> 00:06:38,759
Just to the left of that scary pentacle
and the jar of bloodroot.

64
00:06:38,927 --> 00:06:40,246
Right there.

65
00:06:45,727 --> 00:06:47,479
Thank you. What'd you say?

66
00:06:47,647 --> 00:06:50,525
She's cajun. I told her you wanted
the St. Nicholas candle.

67
00:06:50,687 --> 00:06:53,155
- Is that what you wanted?
- That's the one.

68
00:06:56,967 --> 00:06:59,083
What happened right there?
What did she say?

69
00:06:59,247 --> 00:07:02,159
She said you're nice-Iooking,
but she doesn't trust you.

70
00:07:02,687 --> 00:07:04,439
She didn't say that, did she?

71
00:07:04,607 --> 00:07:07,167
You know what it is?

72
00:07:07,727 --> 00:07:10,844
Jury duty.
I got a summons in the mail.

73
00:07:11,087 --> 00:07:14,397
- I was trying to pray out of it.
- Where's your sense of civic duty?

74
00:07:15,887 --> 00:07:18,117
I flunked civics.

75
00:07:18,287 --> 00:07:23,441
- Do you have any other tips?
- I would go with a St. Catherine candle.

76
00:07:23,767 --> 00:07:25,041
What does she do?

77
00:07:25,207 --> 00:07:28,040
She's the patron saint
of unmarried women and jurors.

78
00:07:28,407 --> 00:07:30,125
- Really?
- Really.

79
00:07:31,007 --> 00:07:33,237
That's not what
that candle really is, is it?

80
00:07:47,407 --> 00:07:51,320
- This your first time in New Orleans?
- No, no.

81
00:07:51,487 --> 00:07:55,924
- I've been here a number of times.
- I had you pegged as a first-timer.

82
00:07:56,927 --> 00:07:58,280
Is that right?

83
00:07:58,527 --> 00:08:00,245
Yeah.

84
00:08:07,487 --> 00:08:09,443
- How's your mother?
- Excuse me?

85
00:08:10,247 --> 00:08:13,876
- She feeling better?
- How do you know about my mother?

86
00:08:14,047 --> 00:08:16,720
She was in the hospital.
Now you care for her at home.

87
00:08:17,807 --> 00:08:20,685
- She had a stroke.
- Your wife wants to put her in a home...

88
00:08:20,847 --> 00:08:24,601
<i>...but</i> you're feeling guilty about that.
You've checked out a few of <i>them...</i>

89
00:08:24,767 --> 00:08:27,645
<i>...and</i> it doesn't feel
like the Christian thing to do.

90
00:08:27,807 --> 00:08:30,526
My advice, reconsider the home.

91
00:08:30,847 --> 00:08:34,078
Better an unhappy mother
than an unfriendly wife.

92
00:08:36,407 --> 00:08:37,681
I'm up here on the right.

93
00:08:41,447 --> 00:08:44,325
- The same thing with guns
and Vicksburg Firearms.

94
00:08:44,727 --> 00:08:46,957
The only thing
that's gonna win this <i>case...</i>

95
00:08:47,127 --> 00:08:50,403
...is because for the first time,
we got a gun company ex-executive...

96
00:08:50,567 --> 00:08:52,956
...who's gonna go up
against his former employer...

97
00:08:53,127 --> 00:08:55,925
...and with good conscience,
he's gonna testify for us.

98
00:08:56,087 --> 00:09:00,478
I promised Celeste that I would win it for
her and all the others that died that day.

99
00:09:00,647 --> 00:09:03,878
You're gonna make history, celeste.
We're gonna do it together.

100
00:09:04,047 --> 00:09:06,277
Thank you for your courage.

101
00:09:14,087 --> 00:09:16,442
We got the Strickland SUV
case at noon.

102
00:09:16,607 --> 00:09:19,360
And celeste, I'll see you
and your son at Arno's at 6.

103
00:09:19,527 --> 00:09:21,518
- As long as we don't...
- Nothing about the case.

104
00:09:21,687 --> 00:09:24,884
This is dinner with you and Henry.
Got time to see her to her car?

105
00:09:25,047 --> 00:09:26,605
- Absolutely.
- Thank you.

106
00:09:26,767 --> 00:09:28,439
- Mr. Rohr.
- Yeah.

107
00:09:28,727 --> 00:09:30,718
Lawrence Green.
Lindus, Hostetler...

108
00:09:30,887 --> 00:09:34,323
Hostetler. Yes, jury consultants,
New York City.

109
00:09:34,487 --> 00:09:36,637
Philadelphia.
Thank you for meeting with me.

110
00:09:36,807 --> 00:09:39,401
Guess how many phone calls
and letters I get...

111
00:09:39,567 --> 00:09:42,081
...from expert jury consultants
such as yourself.

112
00:09:42,247 --> 00:09:44,363
- I can imagine, sir.
- Go on, take a guess.

113
00:09:44,527 --> 00:09:46,199
I appreciate you inviting me here.

114
00:09:46,367 --> 00:09:49,723
- This is more important now. Which one?
- I'm sorry?

115
00:09:49,887 --> 00:09:52,003
I'm off to court.
This is the striped.

116
00:09:52,167 --> 00:09:55,637
- Non-striped? Striped? Non-striped?
- The striped matches your jacket.

117
00:09:55,807 --> 00:09:57,877
Yours is striped because
you're from New York.

118
00:09:58,047 --> 00:10:00,481
- Philadelphia.
- I'm gonna go with the non-striped.

119
00:10:00,647 --> 00:10:03,480
As a clever jury consultant,
you should know...

120
00:10:03,647 --> 00:10:07,560
<i>...that</i> jurors down here don't trust
a lawyer who's too nattily turned out.

121
00:10:07,727 --> 00:10:10,161
- How familiar are you with my case?
- Very, sir.

122
00:10:10,327 --> 00:10:12,283
- You think it's a strong case?
- Yes, sir.

123
00:10:12,447 --> 00:10:16,838
- Do you think it's a winning case?
- People don't win gun cases, Mr. Rohr.

124
00:10:17,887 --> 00:10:19,764
I think I can help you with that, sir.

125
00:10:21,647 --> 00:10:23,478
There's gotta be another
commuter flight.

126
00:10:23,647 --> 00:10:26,207
Can you try one in Richmond
or Atlanta?

127
00:10:27,567 --> 00:10:29,956
I gotta call you back. He's here.

128
00:10:32,127 --> 00:10:35,358
You represent the widow of a man
shot by a Vicksburg Firearms gun.

129
00:10:35,527 --> 00:10:37,677
They're finding out things about <i>jurors...</i>

130
00:10:37,847 --> 00:10:39,997
- ...their spouses don't know.
- Is that right?

131
00:10:40,167 --> 00:10:42,840
And the word is the defense
has retained...

132
00:10:43,007 --> 00:10:45,362
...Rankin Fitch as their
lead jury consultant.

133
00:10:45,527 --> 00:10:47,085
Rankin Fitch?

134
00:10:47,247 --> 00:10:48,726
- You don't...?
- I know who he is.

135
00:10:51,807 --> 00:10:56,278
- Mr. Fitch, how was your flight?
- Fine. We up and running, Miss Monroe?

136
00:10:56,447 --> 00:11:00,725
We are. Kaufman's inside with Birk,
and the kid from MIT, Lamb, is here.

137
00:11:00,887 --> 00:11:02,923
What about Broussard,
forensic linguistics?

138
00:11:03,087 --> 00:11:06,363
Out of Rochester.
He missed his flight. He'll be here by 3.

139
00:11:06,527 --> 00:11:08,404
- Who's our backup?
- He'll be here by 3.

140
00:11:08,567 --> 00:11:11,764
- Who is our backup?
- Levon Raines out of Dallas.

141
00:11:11,927 --> 00:11:16,159
Call Mr. Broussard. Tell him
his service is no longer required.

142
00:11:16,327 --> 00:11:19,125
- See what time Raines can be here.
- Yes, sir.

143
00:11:19,287 --> 00:11:20,766
Mr. Fitch.

144
00:11:28,767 --> 00:11:30,837
Tell me why I need a jury consultant.

145
00:11:31,007 --> 00:11:33,521
Fitch will scientifically
pick jurors predisposed...

146
00:11:33,687 --> 00:11:37,441
...in his favor by using surveillance,
wiretaps, psych profiles, graphology...

147
00:11:37,607 --> 00:11:39,598
- Where's my car?
- Where you parked it.

148
00:11:39,767 --> 00:11:42,839
- We're going together.
- Sir, I have a master's in <i>psychology...</i>

149
00:11:43,007 --> 00:11:47,762
...from the University of Chicago. I know
handwriting. I know this stuff, I do.

150
00:11:49,887 --> 00:11:53,675
Delores Kinnerly, registered Democrat,
46 years of age, unmarried...

151
00:11:53,847 --> 00:11:56,998
...occupational therapist,
devout cat lover.

152
00:11:57,167 --> 00:11:59,522
Look how she turns
from the man walking his dog.

153
00:11:59,687 --> 00:12:03,839
- She's self-conscious about her weight.
- Maybe she just hates dogs.

154
00:12:04,927 --> 00:12:06,155
- Good morning.
- Morning.

155
00:12:06,327 --> 00:12:08,124
Freeze that, Mr. Lamb.

156
00:12:11,887 --> 00:12:13,525
We love fat women, people.

157
00:12:15,047 --> 00:12:17,402
They're tight-fisted, unsympathetic.

158
00:12:17,567 --> 00:12:22,436
I want her on my jury. Let's find 11
more jurors and three alternates like her.

159
00:12:22,687 --> 00:12:25,838
- Who's next?
- Jerry Fernandez, 40, Puerto Rican...

160
00:12:26,007 --> 00:12:27,406
...works for a moving company.

161
00:12:27,567 --> 00:12:29,683
<i>I got 35 years experience</i>
<i>in courtrooms...</i>

162
00:12:29,847 --> 00:12:33,203
...and my instincts for picking juries
have served me nicely so far.

163
00:12:33,367 --> 00:12:37,280
- I wanna thank you for your time.
- I flew down here on my own dime.

164
00:12:37,447 --> 00:12:39,403
- Why?
- Because I...

165
00:12:39,967 --> 00:12:43,516
- Because I believe in this case.
- Why?

166
00:12:45,527 --> 00:12:48,883
- I believe in a world without guns.
- That's very sweet, but naive.

167
00:12:53,687 --> 00:12:56,997
- Thirty percent.
- I'm sorry. Excuse me?

168
00:12:57,247 --> 00:13:01,126
Thirty percent of your usual fee.
You're hired, strictly probationary status.

169
00:13:01,287 --> 00:13:04,324
- You don't wanna check out my résumé?
- Already did.

170
00:13:04,487 --> 00:13:06,478
It's impressive.

171
00:13:09,287 --> 00:13:10,879
<i>- Here's your thing.</i>
<i>- What do you got?</i>

172
00:13:11,207 --> 00:13:12,925
- "The following are exempt:
- I read it.

173
00:13:13,087 --> 00:13:16,636
- Not a resident of New Orleans..."
- That won't work. What am I gonna say?

174
00:13:16,807 --> 00:13:18,718
I'm gonna tell them
I'll pack and leave?

175
00:13:18,887 --> 00:13:22,357
Number two. Pack up and leave?
You ain't got nothing to pack.

176
00:13:22,527 --> 00:13:25,485
No, it's true. They own you.
One thing you can do.

177
00:13:25,647 --> 00:13:27,205
Leave the country.

178
00:13:27,367 --> 00:13:29,756
- Why am I gonna leave?
- Church convention.

179
00:13:29,927 --> 00:13:32,885
Sex change. You're leaving
because you're becoming a woman.

180
00:13:33,607 --> 00:13:36,167
- You own a goat farm.
- This thing is a disaster.

181
00:13:36,327 --> 00:13:37,919
I got my life and work.

182
00:13:38,087 --> 00:13:41,557
- And I got my training. The Challenge.
- Oh, wait a sec.

183
00:13:41,847 --> 00:13:44,805
- You could claim hardship.
- It's 8 weeks away. I can't do it.

184
00:13:44,967 --> 00:13:47,606
- I can't do it.
- You got the challenge. You can't go.

185
00:13:47,767 --> 00:13:51,316
Hold on, check this. "If you have
been convicted of a felony..."

186
00:13:51,487 --> 00:13:53,239
Have you been convicted of a felony?

187
00:13:53,407 --> 00:13:55,318
- No.
- You should commit a felony.

188
00:13:55,847 --> 00:13:58,236
- Commit a crime.
- Are you serious?

189
00:13:58,407 --> 00:14:00,477
It doesn't have to be a bad crime.

190
00:14:00,647 --> 00:14:04,276
- I should commit a crime?
- You're asking to get out of it, right?

191
00:14:04,447 --> 00:14:06,278
You registered to vote.

192
00:14:06,447 --> 00:14:09,598
If you register to vote,
then they got you in the jury pool.

193
00:14:10,007 --> 00:14:11,884
We need to de-register him.

194
00:14:12,047 --> 00:14:14,720
<i>One day, I'm gonna organize,</i>
<i>throw half this stuff away.</i>

195
00:14:15,167 --> 00:14:17,362
<i>What's that, Walther PPK?</i>
<i>That's a nice piece.</i>

196
00:14:17,527 --> 00:14:20,166
<i>That's the same gun James Bond uses.</i>
<i>You know that?</i>

197
00:14:20,327 --> 00:14:22,841
<i>Really? You can 't be too safe</i>
<i>these days.</i>

198
00:14:23,007 --> 00:14:26,124
<i>- Walking on the streets, all alone.</i>
- Smooth, Maxine.

199
00:14:26,327 --> 00:14:29,444
<i>It's easier to find an honest firearm</i>
<i>these days than a good man.</i>

200
00:14:30,207 --> 00:14:33,040
<i>- Know how to use it?</i>
<i>- My brother took me to the dump once.</i>

201
00:14:33,207 --> 00:14:35,163
<i>Let me take you down</i>
<i>to the firing range.</i>

202
00:14:35,367 --> 00:14:37,483
- Thattaboy.
<i>- I'll show you how to shoot.</i>

203
00:14:37,647 --> 00:14:40,719
<i>- I got a few ideas.</i>
<i>- I bet.</i>

204
00:14:40,887 --> 00:14:42,400
Nice job, Maxine.

205
00:14:43,047 --> 00:14:46,005
Frank Herrera, Cuban, 43 years old...

206
00:14:46,167 --> 00:14:49,682
...retired Marine sergeant, served
in Panama and Grenada, twice divorced.

207
00:14:49,847 --> 00:14:51,883
Now he cleans swimming pools.

208
00:14:52,127 --> 00:14:55,005
Fair to say he misses
his former position of authority.

209
00:14:55,167 --> 00:14:58,284
I think Herrera would make
a good foreman. Don't you, Mr. Cable?

210
00:14:58,447 --> 00:15:04,204
I'm only lead counsel for defense. I don't
pretend to know about jury selection.

211
00:15:04,367 --> 00:15:06,323
- Really?
- Really.

212
00:15:06,487 --> 00:15:08,557
- Who's next?
- Nicholas Easter.

213
00:15:08,727 --> 00:15:12,242
Thirty-four, co-manager of Game Trader
in the Esplanade Mall.

214
00:15:12,407 --> 00:15:15,843
- He's gonna love this.
- Watch me hit this lady in the head.

215
00:15:16,007 --> 00:15:18,157
- See how her head explodes?
- It explodes.

216
00:15:18,327 --> 00:15:20,557
<i>Don 't hit her. Hit the bad guy.</i>

217
00:15:20,727 --> 00:15:23,116
<i>- I can try? Show me how to hold it.</i>
<i>- Give it a shot.</i>

218
00:15:24,047 --> 00:15:25,639
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

219
00:15:25,807 --> 00:15:27,957
I threw in this little sniper game.

220
00:15:28,127 --> 00:15:31,722
- I thought you might like it.
- I wrote down my phone number.

221
00:15:31,887 --> 00:15:34,640
<i>Oh, okay. That's a local number.</i>
<i>You're here.</i>

222
00:15:34,807 --> 00:15:36,081
- We're close.
- Right on.

